-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-10-06/merchant-commodity-fund-said-to-make-12-7-last-month-set-for-annual-gain.html
(Corrects to including fees in first paragraph of story
first published Oct. 6.)  The Merchant Commodity Fund climbed
12.7 percent last month, bringing its return to investors this
year including fees to 7.5 percent, said three people with
direct knowledge of the matter.  The fund is heading for its seventh consecutive annual gain
since it started in 2004, according to fund data. The people
declined to be identified as the information isnâ€™t public. Hedge
funds globally returned 1.7 percent on average in September and
1.9 percent in the first nine months, according to Chicago-based
Hedge Fund Research Inc., based on an index of more than 200
such investment pools.  The Merchant Commodity Fund, run by Singapore-based Michael
Coleman and Zug, Switzerland-based Doug King, invests in
agriculture and energy and managed $1.1 billion as of July 30,
according to data compiled by Bloomberg. The fund returned 5.2
percent in 2009 and 24 percent in 2008, fund data show. Coleman,
49, and King, 43, are former Cargill Inc. traders.  To contact the reporter on this story:
